Something wicked this way comes.  This is it, Adam, that grieves me; and the spirit of my father, which I think is within me, begins to mutiny against this servitude.  My lord, the roynish clown, at whom so oft Your Grace was wont to laugh, is also missing.   And why, sir, must they so?  The why is plain as way to parish church: He that a fool doth very wisely hit Doth very foolishly, although he smart, Not to seem senseless of the bob; if not, The wise man's folly is anatomiz'd Even by the squand'ring glances of the fool.

Neither a borrower or a lender be.  Brevity is the soul of wit.  What's mine is yours and what is yours is mine.  Let me love him for that; and do you love him because I do. Look, here comes the Duke. I think he be transform'd into a beast; For I can nowhere find him like a man.

data.html:
Welcome to BOM Squad, the free search and inventory tool created for and by DIY audio hardware enthusiasts! BOM Squad converts static component lists into interactive shopping lists cross-referenced against a database of common components from Tayda, Mouser, and other retailers. Once you’ve sourced your components, BOM Squad helps you manage your personal inventory of components. And because your shopping list knows what’s in your inventory, BOM Squad eliminates redundant orders and helps you repurpose extra components for future builds.


Say goodbye to the headache of managing complex spreadsheets and double checking them against PDFs and supplier websites! BOM Squad eliminates this tedious manual work.


But it doesn’t end there. BOM Squad’s community features crowdsource information about components. Want to know how a certain diode sounds in a fuzz distortion circuit? Need to find an alternative to a component that’s been discontinued? Each component is reviewed in relation to a particular build. No more searching through forum archives. BOM Squad preserve this community wisdom in a single place that’s purpose built for the DIY community.


BOM Squad is open source and the code is freely availible on GitHub, but web hosting isn’t cheap. Please support the project on Ko-fi for $3 or $10 per month and help keep us free and online. And to thank you for your support, Ko-fi subscribers get to the choose which features and projects we add next!

data.html:
Values

Community Driven
Over 95% of audio hardware manufacturers are either sole proprietors or small businesses. We want to give back by building a platform that supports grassroots artists, whether they be consumers, hobbyists, or manufacturers, by making access to knowledge and components easier for everyone.
Free Forever
We’re committed to keeping BOM Squad free to use forever. Although we considered a “freemium” model, we would rather make BOM Squad a tool that’s available to everyone. To that end, we’ve chosen to experiment with crowdfunding instead.
Open Source
Our platform thrives on transparency. Explore our codebase on GitHub and contribute directly to our codebase. We welcome experienced engineers and new contributors alike. BOM Squad is a great place to dip your toe into contributing to an open-source codebase!
Robust and Scalable
We’re building a fully-featured tool that is intended to scale. Although our initial aim has been to support the DIY Eurorack community, we aim to expand over time to support DIY guitar pedals, video synthesizers, and creative electronics for use cases beyond the performing arts too.

How it works

From the homepage, select a project you want to build. You can add projects to your personal list of previously-built project or add it to an aspirational list of projects you plan to build.


Each project page contains details about the project, including a links to the manufacturer’s page where the item (PCB, front panel, kit, etc.) can be purchased, the manufacturer’s original bill of materials (BOM), build instructions (if any) and other relevant links.


A key feature of each product page is the interactive BOM. The manufacturer’s original BOM has been converted into a nested table. BOM items (the build requirements) are listed as rows in the top-level table. Clicking on any row in the table reveals a nested table of components which fulfill that BOM item. (Note that if a project exists in several versions, with different PCBs and BOMs, each version is listed as tabs along the top of the table.)

data.caption: The interactive BOM for the Triple Sloth module by Nonlinearcircuits, showing different versions of the PCB.

data.html: The interactive BOM for the Triple Sloth module by Nonlinearcircuits, showing different versions of the PCB.

The nested table underneath each rows reveals a list of components which fulfill a particular BOM item. Each component displays a few key attributes, including price and a supplier ID number which links to the supplier website. There’s also a community review, which represents how well a component works for a particular BOM list item in a particular build. Community reviews do not represent the quality of components apart from their use in particular projects.

data.caption: Component that fulfill the 10uF item from a BOM.

data.html: Component that fulfill the 10uF item from a BOM.

Signed-in users can add components to their inventory or to a “shopping list” of components they intend to acquire for a particular project. You may add components to your inventory/shopping list or edit the quantity in the inventory/shopping list directly. If you’re adding a component to your inventory, you can also specify the location where you store the component.

data.caption: If you're adding a component to your inventory, you can specify storage location. Locations are specified as a comma-separated list representing a nested structure. For example, you could specify a drawer number which itself contains a box number. This would be the location where you could find the component in the "real world."

data.html: If you're adding a component to your inventory, you can specify storage location. Locations are specified as a comma-separated list representing a nested structure. For example, you could specify a drawer number which itself contains a box number. This would be the location where you could find the component in the "real world."

As a signed-in user, if your inventory contains sufficient components to fulfill a particular item in a BOM, a folder icon is displayed in the interactive BOM. The BOM row will be light yellow. If your shopping list contains sufficient components to fulfill a particular item in a BOM, a cart icon is displayed in the interactive BOM. The BOM row will also be light yellow. If both your inventory and shopping list both contain sufficient components to fulfill a particular item in a BOM, both items will be displayed and the row will be a darker shade of yellow. This feature is intended to help verify that a particular project is possible with the components you posses or intend to acquire. However, currently the feature does not check whether a separate planned build also requires a particular component (overlapping requirements). Use the shopping list in the user account page to verify that you are purchasing sufficient components for each BOM list item.

data.caption: The interactive BOM uses yellow highlights and icons to indicate if your inventory or shopping list meets an item's requirements. Darker yellow means both sources meet the requirements.

SMD pads suit sod-123- 2 or similar. Schottky diode. Dot on PCB indicates CATHODE (stripe on component) Or use a resettable fuse or just a 10R 0805. Some Schottky diodes at Mouser: PMEG2005EGWX SCHOTTKY RECT, AEC-Q101, 20V, SOD-123-2, PMEG2005EH DIODE, SCHOTTKY, 0.5A, 20V

The resistors marked 10k are for driving the LEDs. You can adjust these to a higher value if your LEDs are too bright, but do not go lower than 10k. If your LEDs are not bright enough, get different 3mm LEDs.

0805, RL sets the LED brightness, 4k7 is good for red/blue. For

fields.name: Ming Rod
fields.description:
For synthesizer enthusiasts interested in experimental sound, Tom Oberheim's unique "Ring Modulator" design offers adjustable pots for phase difference and input attenuation, despite potential flaws that might require careful tuning. This approach adds special character and appeal but has remained uncreated due to its complexity.

The concept originated in Oberheim's 1970 paper, where he detailed how transformers in traditional diode ring modulators can be replaced with transistors. Though more efficient alternatives are available, this design presents an intriguing option for those willing to explore unconventional sound techniques.

fields.name: Triple Sloth
fields.description: This module is a unique ensemble of three Sloth chaos circuits, each operating at distinct rates: Torpor travels around strange attractors in 15-30 seconds, Apathy in 60-90 seconds, and Inertia, going rogue without controls, in 30-40 minutes. Apathy and Torpor have adjustable pots, not for frequencies, but for influencing the duration signals stay around different strange attractors, and they have CV inputs which can add a twist of predictability or voltage jumps to the chaos. Finally, each Sloth provides X, Y, and Z outputs from different circuit stages, with the Z outputs also feeding into a Difference Rectifier, which creates additional outputs based on the sum of voltage values from each circuit.

fields.name: Let's Splosh
fields.description: Eight rectifiers that handle four input signals. It can manage both audio and CV simultaneously. With its 16 outputs, it remixes and reshapes the four inputs, delivering 16 varied signals. Essentially, it jumbles the input signals, spreading them across your setup.

fields.name: 4hp Mix
fields.description: The simplest Nonlinearcircuits module and a great module for people new to SMD soldering to start with. There are 4 potentiometers. The 4th pot applies an offset when nothing is patched in.
